Supervised Learning Project : Bank Personal Loan Modeling¶

Thera Bank Personal Loan Campaign¶

Data Description:¶

The dataset contains data on 5000 customers. The data include customer demographic information (age, income, etc.), the customer's relationship with the bank (mortgage, securities account, etc.), and the customer response to the last personal loan campaign (Personal Loan). Among these 5000 customers, only 480 (= 9.6%) accepted the personal loan that was offered to them in the earlier campaign.

Context:¶

This case is about a bank (Thera Bank) whose management wants to explore ways of converting its liability customers to personal loan customers (while retaining them as depositors). A campaign that the bank ran last year for liability customers showed a healthy conversion rate of over 9% success. This has encouraged the retail marketing department to devise campaigns with better target marketing to increase the success ratio with a minimal budget.

Attribute Information:¶

  • ID: Customer ID

  • Age: Customer's age in completed years

  • Experience: #years of professional experience

  • Income: Annual income of the customer ($000)

  • ZIP Code: Home Address ZIP code

  • Family: Family size of the customer

  • CCAvg: Avg. spending on credit cards per month ($000)

  • Education: Education Level. 1: Undergrad; 2: Graduate; 3: Advanced/Professional

  • Mortgage: Value of house mortgage if any. ($000)

  • Personal Loan: Did this customer accept the personal loan offered in the last campaign?

  • Securities Account: Does the customer have a securities account with the bank?

  • CD Account: Does the customer have a certificate of deposit (CD) account with the bank?

  • Online: Does the customer use internet banking facilities?

  • Credit card: Does the customer use a credit card issued by the bank?

Objective:¶

The classification goal is to predict the likelihood of a liability customer buying personal loans.

Domain: Banking¶

Steps and tasks:¶

  1. Import the datasets and libraries, check datatype, statistical summary, shape, null values or incorrect imputation.(5 marks)

  2. EDA: Study the data distribution in each attribute and target variable, share your findings (20 marks)

  • Number of unique in each column?

  • Number of people with zero mortgage?

  • Number of people with zero credit card spending per month?

  • Value counts of all categorical columns

  • Univariate and Bivariate

  • Get data model ready

  1. Split the data into training and test set in the ratio of 70:30 respectively (5 marks)

  2. Use Logistic Regression model to predict whether the customer will take personal loan or not. Print all the metrics related for evaluating the model performance (15 marks)

  3. Check different parameters of Logistic Regression and give your reasoning whether the model performance is affected due to it or not? (10 marks)

  4. Give Business understanding of your model? (5 marks)

## Create a function to get confusion matrix in a proper format
def pltConfusionMatrix(actual, predicted):
    cm = confusion_matrix(actual, predicted)
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True,  fmt='.2f', xticklabels=[0,1], yticklabels=[0,1])
    plt.ylabel('Observed')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted')
    plt.show()

# Let's implement the solver function
def solverScore(solver_list, penalty_val):
    train_score=[]
    test_score=[]
    solver = solver_list

    for i in solver:
        model = LogisticRegression(random_state=15, penalty=penalty_val, C = 0.75, solver=i)  # changing values of solver
        model.fit(X_train, y_train) 
        y_predict = model.predict(X_test)     
        train_score.append(round(model.score(X_train, y_train),3))
        test_score.append(round(model.score(X_test, y_test),3))
    
    print("Solvers are {}".format(solver))
    print()
    print("Train_scores are {}".format(train_score))
    print()
    print("Test score are {}".format(test_score))

Insights:

  • The solver 'newton-cg' gives the highest training(0.965) and test(0.956) accuracy for the penalty L2
  • The solver 'liblinear' gives the highest training(0.961) and test(0.955) accuracy for the penalty L1
  • There is no significant difference between the solver for saga for penalty L1 and L2
  • Highest accuracy is almost same for 'l1' with 'liblinear' and 'l2' with 'newton-cg

liblinear algorithm works with both panelties so let's choose that for future mmodeling use¶

# let's implement Inverse of regularization strength (C) function for various value of C

def cScore(c_list):
    train_score=[]                                 
    test_score=[]
    C = c_list
    for i in C:
        model = LogisticRegression(random_state=15,penalty='l1', solver='liblinear',class_weight=None, C=i)  # changing values of C
        model.fit(X_train, y_train) 
        y_predict = model.predict(X_test)     
        train_score.append(round(model.score(X_train,y_train),3))
        test_score.append(round(model.score(X_test, y_test),3))
    
    print("Inverse of regularization strength (C) are {}".format(C))
    print()
    print("Train_scores are {}".format(train_score))
    print()
    print("Test score are {}".format(test_score))

6 Give Business understanding of your model? (5 marks)¶

Confusion matrix means

True Positive (observed=1,predicted=1):

Predicted that campaign will convert its liability customers to personal loan customers

False Positive (observed=0,predicted=1):

Predicted that the campaign will convert liabilty customer to Personal loan customer but the liability customers will not convert to personal loan customers

True Negative (observed=0,predicted=0):

Predicted that campaign will not convert its liability customers to personal loan customers

False Negative (observed=1,predicted=0):

predicted that the customer will not convert from liability customer to personal loan customer but the actual customer can be converted to personal loan customer.

Bank wants to convert the liabilty customers to personal loan customer and the model data shows following:

  1. There are TP=86 customer will be converted personal loan after campaign
  2. There are TN=1350 customer will not be converted to personal loan after campaing
  3. There are FP=11 customers. If this number is high then the bank's marketing spending will be wasted on targeting wrong customers but this numer is small so bank is relatively in safe position to address it's maketing and won't waste more money
  4. Also FN=53 shows that bank will miss the customer that can actually be converted to a personal loan customer.

With tuning the parameters and changing ZIP Code to categorical column, we have significantly improved the precision and recall of the model prediction and the accuracy of this model is: 95.734%.

After achieving the desired accuracy we can deploy the model for practical use. The bank now can predict who will convert to personal loan, They can use the model for upcoming customers.
